@Letxuga007 You can bind the dfs and set colour to be determined by the `region` column and manually set the color values:

geom_line(
  data = bind_rows(nottingham, nottinghamshire),
  aes(x = period, y = number, color = region)
) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("darkgreen", "green")) https://t.co/XHZlncFp50

@Letxuga007 Do it like this and it will be what I think you want:

geom_line(
  data = nottingham,
  color = "green",
  aes(x = period, y = number)
)

@GracoRoza @kaiblin @stefanomammola1 @ClausWilke x2 &lt;- lapply(seq_along(x), function(i) {
  x[[i]]$name &lt;- newnames[i]
  x[[i]]
})

class(x2) &lt;- "x"

This works, but I’m not sure what it buys me over the for loop apart from needing to debug constantly because I forgot to reclass (which is important for my S3 functions).

@kaiblin @GracoRoza @stefanomammola1 @ClausWilke I know I can use 

mapply(function(a, b) {...}, x, newnames)

But sometimes I have to do something more complicated, like check if newnames has a null value and create a name out of the index. And the result still needs to be re-classed if you’re using a custom class.

@kaiblin @GracoRoza @stefanomammola1 @ClausWilke I prefer for loops when I need to iterate over a list with a custom class and change something about it (especially something that relates to the same-index item in another list). 

for (i in seq_along(x)) {
  x[[i]]$name = newnames[i]
}

Is there a non-for way to do this in R?
